{{Infobox venue | name = Movie Madness Video | nickname = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | fullname = | former names = | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = Movie Madness storefront Oct 20 2017.jpg | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = The store's front exterior in 2017 | pushpin_map = Portland | pushpin_mapsize = | pushpin_map_caption = Location in Portland, Oregon | pushpin_label_position = | address = 4320 SE Belmont Street | location = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S. | coordinates = {{Coord|45.51638889|N|122.61722222|W|display=inline,title}} | type = | genre = | broke_ground = | built = | opened = {{Start date|1991}} | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator = | surface = | scoreboard = | production = | cost = | architect = | builder = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | seating_type = | capacity = | suites = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | field_shape = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = | embedded = | website = {{URL|moviemadnessvideo.com}} | publictransit = }} '''Movie Madness Video''' is a [[video rental shop]] and museum of [[film history]] in [[Portland, Oregon]]'s [[Sunnyside, Portland, Oregon|Sunnyside]] neighborhood, in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pdxmonthly.com/articles/2017/2/20/why-movie-madness-owner-mike-clark-doesn-t-feel-threatened-by-netflix|title=Why Movie Madness Owner Mike Clark Doesn't Feel Threatened by Netflix|date=March 2017|work=[[Portland Monthly]]|accessdate=October 11, 2017|issn=1546-2765}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Frost|first=Michelle|url=http://www.southeastexaminer.com/2015/06/movie-madness-a-museum-of-movie-history/|title=Movie Madness: A Museum of Movie History|date=June 1, 2015|work=The Southeast Examiner|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=October 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amc.com/talk/2008/05/movie-madness-video|title=Site of the Week – Movie Madness Video|date=May 2008|website=[[AMC Networks]]|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/revenge-of-the-video-store-1480161604|title=Revenge of the Video Store|first=Erin Geiger|last=Smith|date=26 November 2016|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[News Corp]] ([[Dow Jones & Company]])|issn=0099-9660|oclc=781541372}}</ref>
==History== The store was opened by Hollywood film editor Mike Clark in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|last=Turnquist|first=Kristi|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/tv/2017/10/save_movie_madness_campaign_ai.html|title='Save Movie Madness' campaign aims to preserve a Portland video landmark|date=October 11, 2017|work=[[The Oregonian]]|accessdate=October 11, 2017|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|location=Portland, Oregon|issn=8750-1317}}</ref>
In October 2017, [[Hollywood Theatre (Portland, Oregon)|Hollywood Theatre]] launched a [[Kickstarter]] campaign to purchase and preserve the store.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kgw.com/news/campaign-underway-to-save-eclectic-movie-madness-video-store/482525289|title=Campaign underway to save eclectic Movie Madness video store|date=October 11, 2017|publisher=[[KGW]]|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Crowell|first=Cameron|url=http://www.portlandmercury.com/feature/2017/10/11/19380108/the-hollywood-theatre-wants-to-save-film-history-but-first-it-needs-to-save-movie-madness|title=The Hollywood Theatre Wants to Save Film History—But First, It Needs to Save Movie Madness|date=October 11, 2017|work=[[The Portland Mercury]]|accessdate=October 11, 2017|publisher=Index Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=http://www.wweek.com/arts/2017/10/11/portlands-longest-running-video-rental-store-is-in-danger-of-closing-so-the-hollywood-theatre-is-stepping-in-to-save-it/|title=Portland’s Longest-Running Video Rental Store Is in Danger of Closing, So the Hollywood Theatre Is Stepping in To Save It|date=October 11, 2017|work=[[Willamette Week]]|accessdate=October 11, 2017|publisher=City of Roses Newspapers|location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref>
